{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3534993,"name":"Kegan Cherry","username":"kegancherry","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/kegancherry/{size}/266518_2.png","created_at":"2025-02-21T02:23:20.239Z","cooked":"<p>Hey everyone,</p>
<p>I’m a rookie programmer for Team 7312, and we’ve been running into an issue with our elevator, elbow, and wrist mechanisms. When no command is being actively run, all three mechanisms fall due to gravity instead of holding their position. Our expectation is that these mechanisms should stay in place when idle, but right now, they drop unless a command is continuously running to maintain their position.</p>
<h3><a name="p-3534993-robot-overview-1" class="anchor" href="#p-3534993-robot-overview-1"></a><strong>Robot Overview</strong></h3>
<p><div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/f/b/fb5ca9466b1f7f5e0b4715c85d70b8a31d2a4e68.jpeg" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/fb5ca9466b1f7f5e0b4715c85d70b8a31d2a4e68" title="image"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/f/b/fb5ca9466b1f7f5e0b4715c85d70b8a31d2a4e68_2_521x500.jpeg" alt="image" data-base62-sha1="zREmZyTmEfCsWULROSpRJp2t9a0" width="521" height="500" srcset="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/f/b/fb5ca9466b1f7f5e0b4715c85d70b8a31d2a4e68_2_521x500.jpeg, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/f/b/fb5ca9466b1f7f5e0b4715c85d70b8a31d2a4e68_2_781x750.jpeg 1.5x, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/f/b/fb5ca9466b1f7f5e0b4715c85d70b8a31d2a4e68_2_1042x1000.jpeg 2x" data-dominant-color="332A2A"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">image</span><span class="informations">1065×1021 116 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div></p>
<p>Our robot features a cascading elevator system powered by two TalonFX Krakens. The elevator is responsible for raising and lowering our manipulator and is designed to move smoothly between various positions. Additionally, our arm system consists of two joints: the elbow and the wrist. The elbow and wrist are each powered by a NEO motor controlled by a SparkMax. Both joints are meant to allow for precise positioning of the manipulator so that we can efficiently pick up and score game pieces.</p>
<p>For control, we are using a combination of absolute and relative encoders to track the position of each mechanism. The elevator utilizes a Canandmag absolute encoder for position feedback, while the elbow and wrist each have an absolute encoder, with their relative encoders being reset to the absolute encoder’s position at initialization. Each mechanism also has its own <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> controller that is used to reach and maintain a set position when actively commanded.</p>
<p>If you’d like more details on our robot’s design and progress, you can check out our full build thread here: <a href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/t/t3-robotics-7312-2025-season-thread/481093/6">T3 Robotics 7312 - 2025 Season Thread</a>.</p>
<h3><a name="p-3534993-the-issue-were-facing-2" class="anchor" href="#p-3534993-the-issue-were-facing-2"></a><strong>The Issue We’re Facing</strong></h3>
<p>Right now, whenever we stop actively commanding the elevator, elbow, or wrist, they immediately start to fall. We’ve already set the motors to <strong>Brake Mode</strong> on both the TalonFX and SparkMax controllers, but this doesn’t seem to be enough to prevent them from moving under their own weight. When a command is running, the <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> controller works as expected, holding the setpoint and maintaining position. However, as soon as the command stops executing, the mechanism no longer holds its position and begins to drop due to gravity.</p>
<p>This issue is particularly problematic because it means that we always have to be running a command just to keep the mechanisms in place. Ideally, they should be able to hold their position on their own when idle, but right now, that’s not happening. We’re not sure if this is an issue with how we’re structuring our commands, a limitation of how our control loops are set up, or if there’s something else we’re missing.</p>
<p>For additional safety, we have both soft limits and physical limit switches enabled on the elbow and wrist. These help ensure that we don’t overextend or damage the mechanisms, but they don’t do anything to prevent the falling issue. The elevator also has forward and reverse limits set to prevent over-travel, but again, this doesn’t help with holding position when idle.</p>
<h3><a name="p-3534993-what-we-need-help-with-3" class="anchor" href="#p-3534993-what-we-need-help-with-3"></a><strong>What We Need Help With</strong></h3>
<p>Since I’m still learning, I’m trying to figure out what’s missing in our approach. We know that Brake Mode helps reduce movement, but it isn’t enough to fully hold the mechanisms in place. We also know that the <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> controllers are working when actively running, but as soon as the command stops, there’s nothing keeping the mechanisms at their last position.</p>
<p>How should we be handling this? Should we be structuring our commands differently so that the mechanisms always maintain their last known position? Are there settings within the SparkMax or TalonFX that we should be enabling to help with this? I’d really appreciate any feedback, especially from teams who have dealt with a similar issue before.</p>
<p>Thanks in advance for any help you can provide!</p>
<h3><a name="p-3534993-tldr-4" class="anchor" href="#p-3534993-tldr-4"></a><strong>TL;DR</strong></h3>
<p>Our elevator, elbow, and wrist mechanisms all fall when no command is running. Brake Mode is enabled but isn’t enough to hold them in place. The <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> controllers work while actively running, but once they stop, the mechanisms immediately start to drop. Looking for guidance on how to fix this so that the mechanisms stay in place when idle.</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2025-02-21T02:23:20.239Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":88,"reads":353,"readers_count":352,"score":515.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":492539,"topic_slug":"elevator-elbow-and-wrist-falling-when-not-commanded","display_username":"Kegan Cherry","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/t/t3-robotics-7312-2025-season-thread/481093/6","internal":true,"reflection":false,"title":"T3 Robotics 7312┃2025 Season Thread","clicks":4}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":73648,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programmer"},"post_url":"/t/elevator-elbow-and-wrist-falling-when-not-commanded/492539/1","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3534998,"name":"Eli Barnett","username":"Oblarg","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/oblarg/{size}/161