<p>Don’t stop the controllers, then.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2025-02-21T02:29:42.537Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":297,"readers_count":296,"score":184.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":492539,"topic_slug":"elevator-elbow-and-wrist-falling-when-not-commanded","display_username":"Eli Barnett","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":8}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":12381,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Robot apartments! invisible suburbs! skeleton treasuries!"},"post_url":"/t/elevator-elbow-and-wrist-falling-when-not-commanded/492539/2","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":7},{"id":"-1","type":"emoji","count":1},{"id":"point_up","type":"emoji","count":1},{"id":"question","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":10,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":true,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3534999,"name":"Jeffrey Davis","username":"Practicality","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/practicality/{size}/208492_2.png","created_at":"2025-02-21T02:31:17.113Z","cooked":"<p>There are 3 common solutions to this. You can either increase the gear ratio so that the braking torque is sufficient to hold it still, you can continously apply some power to resist gravity and hold it still, or you can add some springs or surgical tubing to counteract gravity.</p>
<p>They all have pros and cons. Increasing gear ratio will likely make your mechanism slower, but it’s pretty reliable. Applying power makes it so you don’t lose speed but you will drain some battery throughout the match. Using springs requires some mechanical knowledge and probably adds weight/uses space, but doesn’t drain battery or slow things down.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2025-02-21T02:33:11.414Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":298,"readers_count":297,"score":104.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":492539,"topic_slug":"elevator-elbow-and-wrist-falling-when-not-commanded","display_username":"Jeffrey Davis","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":3}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":62548,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/elevator-elbow-and-wrist-falling-when-not-commanded/492539/3","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":2},{"id":"point_up","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":3,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3535000,"name":"","username":"w1zxrd","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/w1zxrd/{size}/246745_2.png","created_at":"2025-02-21T02:35:07.911Z","cooked":"<p>You’re going to need to supply current to the motors in order to prevent gravity from causing your mechanisms to fall. Brake mode doesn’t actively apply power to the motor to offset spinning, but rather it effectively shorts the motor leads together, which results in the motor being much more difficult to backdrive and stopping much faster if it was powered previously. This is why it works when the robot is disabled, as long as there’s power. My recommendation is to have the controllers running within the subsystem so you can run them periodically (every frame) to calculate the current required to keep it up. Take a look at this example:</p><aside class="onebox githubfolder" data-onebox-src="https://github.com/NEIA-Robotics-9644/2025-Robot-Code/tree/main/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/elevator">
